{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17517121","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17517121"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:51:39+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:51:39+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12761"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12761","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12761"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.44,0.16,0.23,0.11,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5208"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114804"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5208","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5208"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12761"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96807"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"1114"},{"type":"tags","id":"1886"},{"type":"tags","id":"2074"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"2589"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4988"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8832"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8961"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34649"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42809"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43350"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44594"},{"type":"contributions","id":"48426"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114804","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/114804"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 38-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a two-day history of shortness of breath and chest pain. She reports feeling tired for the past couple of weeks and has been walking less than usual due to fatigue. She has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. She is a non-smoker.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with a pulse rate of 80/min, blood pressure 126/74 mmHg, respiratory rate 20/min, SpO2 92% on room air, and temperature 36.9 \u00b0C. On auscultation, she has bilateral wheezing and normal heart sounds. She has no calf tenderness or lower extremity oedema.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHer D-dimer is elevated and her chest X-ray is clear. She subsequently undergoes a CT pulmonary angiogram which is unremarkable apart from a solitary 8 mm solid round nodule in her left upper lobe. There are no calcifications. There is no lymphadenopathy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EShe is treated with salbutamol and discharged home in a stable condition.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Follow-up CT chest in 6-12 months","Bronchoscopy in 1-2 weeks","Transthoracic needle biopsy in 2-4 weeks","Follow-up chest X-ray in 3-6 months","PET-CT scan in 2-4 weeks"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EPulmonary nodules are defined as small, round, or oval-shaped growths in the lung. The management of pulmonary nodules depends on several factors, including the size of the nodule, the presence or absence of certain imaging features, and the patient\u0027s risk factors for lung cancer. This patient has an incidental indeterminate 8 mm nodule which requires further monitoring. She is considered low risk (\u0026lt;5% probability of malignancy) based on her lack of smoking history, lack of family history of lung cancer and young age. According to the Fleischner Society guidelines for patients over 35 years of age, a \u003Cstrong\u003Efollow-up CT chest in 6-12 months\u003C/strong\u003E would be the most appropriate next step for an 8 mm nodule in a low risk patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe Fleischner guidelines stratify nodule management based on risk of malignancy. Nodules typically less than 6 mm in diameter with smooth borders have a low probability of being cancerous. Nodules larger than 8 mm, in the upper lobes (more so the right upper lung), multiple nodules, irregular borders, spiculation, cavitation or growing solid component have a higher probability of being cancerous.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Efollow-up chest X-ray in 3-6 months\u003C/strong\u003E would be less sensitive than CT in detecting changes in the nodule. \u003Cstrong\u003EBronchoscopy in 1-2 weeks\u003C/strong\u003E is not necessary as there is no evidence the nodule is malignant or requires invasive intervention at this stage. \u003Cstrong\u003ETransthoracic needle biopsy in 2-4 weeks\u003C/strong\u003E may be considered for suspicious features or concern for malignancy, but is not indicated given this patient\u0027s low risk and indeterminate nodule. \u003Cstrong\u003EPET-CT scan in 2-4 weeks\u003C/strong\u003E would be indicated for intermediate/high risk of malignancy, such as nodules \u0026gt;8 mm, irregular shape, spiculated margins, or risk factors like smoking, asbestos exposure, or family history of lung cancer.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Follow-up CT chest is the most appropriate course of action for monitoring a low risk 8 mm lung nodule according to Fleischner guidelines.","The Fleischner Society guidelines provide a framework for the management of incidental pulmonary nodules based on size and risk factors."],"references":["Massion PP, Walker RC. Indeterminate pulmonary nodules: risk for having or for developing lung cancer? Cancer Prev Res (Phila). 2014 Dec;7(12):1173-8. doi: 10.1158/1940-6207.CAPR-14-0364. Epub 2014 Oct 27. PMID: 25348855; PMCID: PMC4829944.","MacMahon H, Naidich DP, Goo JM, et al. Guidelines for Management of Incidental Pulmonary Nodules Detected on CT Images: From the Fleischner Society 2017. Radiology. 2017 Jul;284(1):228-243. doi: 10.1148/radiol.2017161659. Epub 2017 May 9. PMID: 28492857.","Mazzone PJ, Lam L. Evaluating the Patient With a Pulmonary Nodule: A Review. JAMA. 2022 Jan 18;327(3):264-273. doi: 10.1001/jama.2021.24287. PMID: 35040882.","Farjah F, Monsell SE, Smith-Bindman R, et al. Fleischner Society Guideline  Recommendations for Incidentally  Detected Pulmonary Nodules and the  Probability of Lung Cancer. J Am Coll Radiol. 2022; 19:1226-235."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96807"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12761"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96807","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/96807"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-20T14:25:33+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-20T14:26:54+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5208"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114804"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}}